# tinysshd — TinySSH is public-key-only (no password auth path; see
# tools/build-tinyssh.sh). It therefore never reads /etc/shadow or
# /etc/aegis/admin, so it must NOT hold CAP_KIND_AUTH: granting AUTH to the
# most-exposed, most-complex remote-facing daemon means a pre-auth memory-safety
# compromise in its KEX/packet parser would yield read access to the shadow
# hashes + the admin credential (offline-cracking material for the whole
# system). Least privilege: tinysshd needs only baseline caps (it operates the
# socket fd handed in by the sshd frontend and reads its host keys via ordinary
# VFS). Deliberately NO service-tier grants here.
